\n    way in which\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":"\n    is implemented.  In general, using\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":"\n    to construct lists will result in an interlinked structure of pairs in\n    which many individual pairs are shared by many different structures.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_original/ch3-Z-G-17.svg","id":"#fig-","captionHref":"","captionName":"Figure  ","captionBody":[{"body":"\n\t    The list ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":" formed by\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(cons x x)"},{"body":".\n\t  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_original/ch3-Z-G-18.svg","id":"#fig-","captionHref":"","captionName":"Figure  ","captionBody":[{"body":"\n\t    The list ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z2"},{"body":" formed by\n\t    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(cons (list 'a 'b) (list 'a 'b))"},{"body":".\n\t  ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p8","child":[{"body":"\n    In contrast to\n    \n\tfigure ,\n\tfigure \n    shows\n    the structure created by\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":20,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAC8AmETAYwHtiBnGgG0KYBcQByAQ14AjAJRsO3fkOHSgA","body":"(define z2 (cons (list 'a 'b) (list 'a 'b))) "},{"body":"\n    In this structure, the pairs in the two\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(a b)"},{"body":"\n    lists are distinct, although\n    \n\tthe actual symbols are shared.\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-4","body":"4","href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-4"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p9","child":[{"body":"\n    When thought of as a list, ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":" and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z2"},{"body":" both represent \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"the same","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" list:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":21,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFJghiARgJQh5FA","body":"((a b) a b) "},{"body":"\n    In general, sharing is completely undetectable if we operate on lists using\n    only\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":",","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":",\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":".\n    However, if we allow mutators on list structure, sharing becomes\n    significant.  As an example of the difference that sharing can make,\n    consider the following\n    procedure,\n    which modifies the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    of the structure to which it is applied:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":22,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGdcAXAWmoHtaB3B5gQhAA8BKNEclToBjAIYAnTpjHjuPEAHJWzPgN5A","body":"(define (set-to-wow! x)\n  (set-car! (car x) 'wow)\n  x) "},{"body":"\n    Even though ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":" and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z2"},{"body":" are \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"the same","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" structure,\n    applying\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-to-wow!"},{"body":"\n    to them yields different results.  With ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":",\n    altering the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    also changes the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":",\n    because in ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":" the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    and the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    are the same pair.  With ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z2"},{"body":", the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    are distinct, so\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-to-wow!"},{"body":"\n    modifies only the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":":","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":23,"eval":true,"prependLength":4,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAA8RMAbQgZwBcQByAQxYCMBKLrPI0iABeKKgGMA9sToUKPDCKA","body":"z1 ","output":"((a b) a b)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":24,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGdcAXAWmoHtaB3B5gQhAA8BKNEclToBjAIYAnTpjHjuPEAHJWzPgN4YcBEmS7kANoQrVFoxQCMefTUVIgAXinLCGxCtzl8sQ+k2WcHPEA","body":"(set-to-wow! z1) ","output":"((wow b) wow b)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":25,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAC8AmETAYwHtiBnGgG0KYBcQByAQ14AjAJRsO3fkOHSMVIA","body":"z2 ","output":"((a b) a b)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":26,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGdcAXAWmoHtaB3B5gQhAA8BKNEclToBjAIYAnTpjHjuPEAHJWzPgN4YcBEmQBeAJnLCGxCuQA2hCtUWjFAI3mYLVm-Z7uNQ+k2Wd9PIA","body":"(set-to-wow! z2) ","output":"((wow b) a b)"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p10","child":[{"body":"\n\tOne way to detect sharing in list structures is to use the predicate \n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"eq?"},{"body":", which we introduced in\n\tsection  as a way to test whether two \n\tsymbols are equal. More generally, ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(eq? x y)"},{"body":"\n\ttests whether ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"y"},{"body":" are the same object (that is, whether\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"y"},{"body":"\n\tare equal as pointers).\n      \n    Thus, with ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":" and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z2"},{"body":" as defined in\n    \n\tfigure \n\tand ,\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(eq? (car z1) (cdr z1))"},{"body":"\n    is true and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(eq? (car z2) (cdr z2))"},{"body":"\n    is false.\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p11","child":[{"body":"\n    As will be seen in the following sections, we can exploit sharing to\n    greatly extend the repertoire of data structures that can be\n    represented by pairs.  On the other hand, sharing can also be\n    \n    dangerous, since modifications made to structures will also affect\n    other structures that happen to share the modified parts.  The mutation\n    operations\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-car!"},{"body":"\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-cdr!"},{"body":"\n    should be used with care; unless we have a good understanding of how our\n    data objects are shared, mutation can have unanticipated\n    results.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-5","body":"5","href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-5"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.15","id":"#ex-3.15","child":[{"body":"\n    Draw box-and-pointer diagrams to explain the effect of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-to-wow!"},{"body":"\n    on the structures ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z1"},{"body":" and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z2"},{"body":" above.\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.16","id":"#ex-3.16","child":[{"body":"\n    Ben Bitdiddle decides to write a\n    procedure\n    to count the number of pairs in any list structure.\n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"It's easy,","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" he reasons.  \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"The number of pairs in\n    any structure is the number in the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    plus the number in the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    plus one more to count the current pair.","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" So Ben writes the following\n    procedure:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":27,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGMB7AV2IBcBaABwENCAnAZxAA8BKNCHKF85YlXrk2nAPx9+g4cpAAGISvIBqctTpMZ3Xaw4Klm5ZVoMW7I5WymB5iyBSL+QA","body":"(define (count-pairs x)\n  (if (not (pair? x))\n      0\n      (+ (count-pairs (car x))\n         (count-pairs (cdr x))\n         1))) "},{"body":"\n    Show that this\n    procedure\n    is not correct.  In particular, draw box-and-pointer diagrams representing\n    list structures made up of exactly three pairs for which Ben's\n    procedure\n    would return 3; return 4; return 7; never return at all.\n    ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":28,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGMB7AV2IBcBaABwENCAnAZxAA8BKNCHKF85YlXrk2nAPx9+g4cpAAGISvIBqctTpMZ3Xaw4Klm5ZVoMW7I5WymB5iyBSLBaIA","body":" "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.17","id":"#ex-3.17","child":[{"body":"\n    Devise a correct version of the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"count-pairs"},{"body":"procedure\n    of exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.16","href":"/sicp/3.3.1#ex-3.16"},{"body":" that returns the number of\n    distinct pairs in any structure.  (Hint: Traverse the structure, maintaining\n    an auxiliary data structure that is used to keep track of which pairs have\n    already been counted.)\n    ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":29,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.18","id":"#ex-3.18","child":[{"body":"\n    Write a\n    procedure\n    that examines a list and\n    \n    determines whether it contains a cycle, that is,\n    whether a program that tried to find the end of the list by taking\n    successive\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"s\n    would go into an infinite loop. Exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.13","href":"/sicp/3.3.1#ex-3.13"},{"body":"\n    constructed such lists.\n    ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":30,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.19","id":"#ex-3.19","child":[{"body":"\n    Redo exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.18","href":"/sicp/3.3.1#ex-3.18"},{"body":" using an algorithm that\n    takes only a constant amount of space.  (This requires a very clever idea.)\n    ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"body":"\n      Define a fast pointer and a slow pointer. The fast pointer goes forward\n      2 steps every time, while the slow pointer goes forward 1 step every time.\n      If there is a cycle in the list, the fast pointer will eventually catch\n      up with the slow pointer.\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":31,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"SUBHEADING","id":"#h2","child":[{"body":"Mutation is just assignment","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p12","child":[{"body":"\n    When we introduced compound data, we observed in\n    section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.1.3","href":"/sicp/2.1.3"},{"body":" that pairs can be represented purely\n    in terms of\n    procedures:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":32,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGMB7YgZxAA8QBPASjRHLyNK8NoAOAQwAuFABYgAtu06dKNbOUy4AjgH5pIAOQUhAJ1aNZc0-JUatu7IZYmzclQBtaZFfv1V9IAEQBVYm4SXCUqAVx9UUIaEABaOJAoAHkAOTAfaVYsk2x+YTFxdiwg3koDEAAvI0wKnT1DIpwCYPIKG0rq2usGoA","body":"(define (cons x y)\n  (define (dispatch m)\n    (cond ((eq? m 'car) x)\n          ((eq? m 'cdr) y)\n          (else (error \"Undefined operation - - CONS\" m))))\n  dispatch)\n\n(define (car z) (z 'car))\n\n(define (cdr z) (z 'cdr)) "},{"body":"\n    The same observation is true for mutable data.  We can implement\n    mutable data objects as\n    procedures\n    using assignment and local state. For instance, we can extend the above\n    pair implementation to handle\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-car!"},{"body":"\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-cdr!"},{"body":"\n    in a manner analogous to the way we implemented bank accounts using\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-account"},{"body":"\n    in section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.1.1","href":"/sicp/3.1.1"},{"body":":\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":33,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGMB7YgZxAA8QBPASjRHLyNPNtwAuAWgYBCEADdWfQeKZT2nHARJlM-Yc3FSZA8c0mtFXFbxyFaABwCGAigAsQAW2NLqxbOUy4AjgH5nEAByCmsAJ2kGV04YpW9-QJDsCJZo2LjfAKdgjSFQsNFpXLE09Mx4rJzBPOTCkFytUtjvABt+clwwsKowkAAiAFUPU1xPKktO20IaECFZkCgAeQA5MD7nIyMOEGwLGzt7dixuVXJ8kAAvaUwL4Pyt45Gz5Mvr26SIo+UeNVz88VupAA7kIJNYWgBXXDGcrvP7hOrA0HgqHGK4Yb6ndTVCi1S4gJFgyHQ7awqrCXEFaSElEkzhXIA","body":"(define (cons x y)\n  (define (set-x! v) (set! x v))\n  (define (set-y! v) (set! y v))\n  (define (dispatch m)\n    (cond ((eq? m 'car) x)\n          ((eq? m 'cdr) y)\n          ((eq? m 'set-car!) set-x!)\n          ((eq? m 'set-cdr!) set-y!)\n          (else (error \"Undefined operation - - CONS\" m))))\n  dispatch)\n\n(define (car z) (z 'car))\n\n(define (cdr z) (z 'cdr))\n\n(define (set-car! z new-value)\n  ((z 'set-car!) new-value)\n  z)\n\n(define (set-cdr! z new-value)\n  ((z 'set-cdr!) new-value)\n  z) "}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p13","child":[{"body":"\n    Assignment is all that is needed, theoretically, to account for the\n    behavior of mutable data.  As soon as we admit\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set!"},{"body":"\n    to our language, we raise all the issues, not only of assignment, but of\n    mutable data in general.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-6","body":"6","href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-6"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.20","id":"#ex-3.20","child":[{"body":"\n    Draw environment diagrams to illustrate the evaluation of the sequence\n    of\n    \n\texpressions\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":34,"eval":true,"prependLength":24,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGMB7YgZxAA8QBPASjRHLyNPNtwAuAWgYBCEADdWfQeKZT2nHARJlM-Yc3FSZA8c0mtFXFbxyFaABwCGAigAsQAW2NLqxbOUy4AjgH5nEAByCmsAJ2kGV04YpW9-QJDsCJZo2LjfAKdgjSFQsNFpXLE09Mx4rJzBPOTCkFytUtjvABt+clwwsKowkAAiAFUPU1xPKktO20IaECFZkCgAeQA5MD7nIyMOEGwLGzt7dixuVXJ8kAAvaUwL4Pyt45Gz5Mvr26SIo+UeNVz88VupAA7kIJNYWgBXXDGcrvP7hOrA0HgqHGK4Yb6ndTVCi1S4gJFgyHQ7awqrCXEFaSElEkzjox4-RhnGj0FAgABMW0xvFulFZzKi7GxFIRz16VxAKAA7F9zlEgA","body":"(define x (cons 1 2))\n(define z (cons x x))\n(set-car! (cdr z) 17)\n\n(car x) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":35,"eval":true,"prependLength":30,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGMB7YgZxAA8QBPASjRHLyNPNtwAuAWgYBCEADdWfQeKZT2nHARJlM-Yc3FSZA8c0mtFXFbxyFaABwCGAigAsQAW2NLqxbOUy4AjgH5nEAByCmsAJ2kGV04YpW9-QJDsCJZo2LjfAKdgjSFQsNFpXLE09Mx4rJzBPOTCkFytUtjvABt+clwwsKowkAAiAFUPU1xPKktO20IaECFZkCgAeQA5MD7nIyMOEGwLGzt7dixuVXJ8kAAvaUwL4Pyt45Gz5Mvr26SIo+UeNVz88VupAA7kIJNYWgBXXDGcrvP7hOrA0HgqHGK4Yb6ndTVCi1S4gJFgyHQ7awqrCXEFaSElEkzjox4-RhnGj0FAgABMW0xvFulFZzKi7GxFIRz16VxAKAA7F9zlEMfLWEA","body":"(car x) ","output":"17"},{"body":"\n    using the \n    \n            procedural \n      \n    implementation of pairs given above.  (Compare\n    exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.11","href":"/sicp/3.2.4#ex-3.11"},{"body":".)\n    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-link-1","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Set-car!"},{"body":" and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set-cdr!"},{"body":" return\n\timplementation-dependent\n\t\n\tvalues.  Like ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set!"},{"body":", they should be used\n\tonly for their effect.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-2","count":2,"href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-link-2","child":[{"body":"We see from this that mutation operations on\n    lists can create \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"garbage","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" that is not part of any accessible\n    structure. We will see in section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"5.3.2","href":"/sicp/5.3.2"},{"body":" that\n    Lisp\n    memory-management systems include a \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"garbage collector","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":", which identifies and recycles the memory\n    space used by unneeded pairs.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-3","count":3,"href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-link-3","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Get-new-pair"},{"body":"\n\tis one of the operations that must be implemented as part of the memory\n\tmanagement required by a Lisp implementation.\n\tWe will discuss this in\n\tsection ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"5.3.1","href":"/sicp/5.3.1"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-4","count":4,"href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-link-4","child":[{"body":"The two pairs are distinct because each call to\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":" returns a new pair.  The\n        symbols are shared; in Scheme there is a\n        \n\tunique symbol with any given\n        name.  Since Scheme provides no way to mutate a symbol, this sharing is\n        undetectable.  Note also that the sharing is what enables us to\n        compare symbols using ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"eq?"},{"body":", which simply checks equality of\n        pointers.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-5","count":5,"href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-link-5","child":[{"body":"The subtleties of dealing with sharing of mutable data\n    objects reflect the underlying issues of \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"sameness","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" and\n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"change","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" that were raised in\n    section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.1.3","href":"/sicp/3.1.3"},{"body":".  We mentioned there\n    that admitting change to our language requires that a compound object must\n    have an \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"identity","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" that is something different from the pieces\n    from which it is composed.  In\n    Lisp,\n    we consider this \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"identity","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" to be the quality that is tested by\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"eq?"},{"body":",\n    i.e., by equality of pointers.  Since in most\n    Lisp\n    implementations a pointer is essentially a memory address, we are\n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"solving the problem","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" of defining the identity of objects by\n    stipulating that a data object \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"itself","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" is the information\n    stored in some particular set of memory locations in the computer.  This\n    suffices for simple\n    Lisp\n    programs, but is hardly a general way to resolve the issue of\n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"sameness","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" in computational models.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-6","count":6,"href":"/sicp/3.3.1#footnote-link-6","child":[{"body":"On the other hand, from the viewpoint of\n    implementation, assignment requires us to modify the environment, which is\n    itself a mutable data structure.  Thus, assignment and mutation are\n    equipotent: Each can be implemented in terms of the other.","tag":"#text"}]}]